  "optimization_hints": [
    "Q1: Vectorized hash aggregation over 60M lineitem rows with high selectivity (98.7%). Use SIMD for SUM/AVG computation. Parallelized scans (32 threads) mandatory—single-thread cannot saturate I/O. Zone maps on l_shipdate (pre-computed min/max per block) skip irrelevant blocks early. Result set: 4 rows.",
    "Q3: Three-way join (customer-orders-lineitem) with medium selectivity (~4.8% final). Use hash join: build on customer (1.5M), probe orders (15M), then probe lineitem (60M). Partial aggregation per morsel, final merge. Top-10 limit avoids full sort—use heap or binary search. Parallelize all stages with 32 threads.",
    "Q6: Selective scan (1.3% combined filter) + scalar aggregation. Branch-free filtering with SIMD for date/discount/qty predicates. Single pass over lineitem. Parallelized row collection, final SUM across threads. No sort/aggregation overhead."
  ],
  "summary": "Workload is OLAP-heavy (analytical scans, multi-way joins, aggregations). Lineitem is the bottleneck fact table (60M rows, 3 queries). Q1 has extremely high selectivity (98.7%) but low cardinality result (4 groups)—hash aggregation dominates. Q3 is join-heavy with multi-way filtering and partial aggregation before top-10 sort. Q6 is selective (1.3% rows) with scalar result. Critical optimizations: (1) Thread parallelism (64 cores available)—morsel-driven execution for scans/joins/aggs. (2) SIMD for filtering and aggregation loops. (3) Zone maps on l_shipdate (high cardinality, range queries in Q1/Q6). (4) Hash aggregation with compact hash tables (Swiss/Robin Hood) for Q1/Q3. (5) Operator fusion (scan+filter+project) to reduce materialization. (6) Top-K partial sort for Q3 instead of full sort. Execution time dominated by I/O on HDD + CPU compute on 60M lineitem rows; parallelism and vectorization are critical."
